An FDA panel voted 21-1 to ban use of OTC cough and cold medicines for children under 2.
It advised better labeling and standardized measuring devices.
Safer treatment for children's cold symptoms includes acetaminophen, humidifiers, saltwater and hydration.
Products labeled "DM" should be avoided.
OTC pediatric medications, of which 800 are sold, have caused convulsions, heart problems, breathing trouble, neurological complications, brain scarring, seizures, and 123 deaths.
Few clinical studies have been done on their effectiveness.
Children with unrecognized heart problems may be harmed.
Antihistamines risk breathing stoppage.
Sedating children to relieve symptoms risks strangulation and SIDS.
